The article discusses how Argentina, Brazil, Canada, Mexico, and the United States are recognizing their role as major agricultural and agricultural input exporters in strengthening global food security. They highlight the challenges of supply disruptions, climate change, and high energy and fertilizer prices in the agricultural sector. The countries affirm the need to stabilize food prices, maximize agricultural yields, and build resilient and sustainable global food systems. They plan to promote best practices to boost crop yields, enhance agricultural production, and improve trade. They aim to maximize food supplies, improve trade and transportation of food, and avoid export bans that disrupt markets. The countries also commit to providing humanitarian assistance to vulnerable populations and supporting increased access to fertilizers. They emphasize the importance of optimizing fertilizer use, enhancing sustainability of water resources and biodiversity, and addressing food insecurity as a global problem.